Building a Pokedex using CNNs¶


Gotta Classify Them All!¶

In this blog I will be attempting to build out a convolutional neural network that classifies 1st gen Pokemon. I wanted to play around with some CNNs and quickly settled on this nostalgic idea. Its hardly an original idea and there are number of other attempts out there, but I wanted to give it a go nonetheless and see if I can improve on what's come before.

The Dataset¶

I originally took this dataset from Kaggle. When training smaller CNNs I noticed they were rapidly over-fitting, and hence I decided to increase the size of the dataset. There's a really neat Python package that downloads Google images called simple-image-downloader. Using this I created a dataset of 26,792 images. I tried to get this as equally spread across Pokemon to avoid class imbalance. I was finding that I was getting many duplicate images for some classes. After removing these the were a range of image numbers for each Pokemon. The downloader also sometimes got incorrect images, or images of multiple Pokemon in one image. I went through the dataset a couple times cleaning it, however, it is still not perfect. I have uploaded my version of the dataset on my Kaggle.

I made a couple of edits to the simple-image-downloader package to stop it from producing an error when a request timed out, so that it would be able to run without me having to restart it. It was this process of restarting that often gave me the duplicate images and hence was an important step. If you'd like to see use my version of simple-image-downloader then please see the Pokedex repository on my Github.

Exploring the Data¶

Like all good data science projects I started with some exploratory data analysis. For this project I will be using Tensorflow, as well as a few other standard libraries to help process and display the data and results.

The plots show a large spread of picture sizes, all the way up to 6000+ pixels. The KDE plot neatly shows that the vast majority of the pictures have heights and widths between 200 and 500 pixels.

Now let's load the data. I'm going to format all the images to 224 x 224, since this is a common image size in the dataset (it is also a key hyperparameter and the choice of 224 will be become evident later).

Note, the data only has 149 classes, as Nidoran was removed from the original dataset. I suspect this is because it takes male and female forms that look different but have the same name, and hence would confuse the model. By the time I realised this I had already boosted the dataset and so didn't go back to add them in. Sorry Nidoran.

To load the data I will set up a Tensorflow pipeline which will work efficiently when training the model and help implement data augmentation.

In [16]:

We can see the range of images per class goes from around 140 to 240, with the median around 180. This might seem a large spread, but is a much more stable spread than the original dataset. It will be interesting to see if the number of images per class impacts the accuracy of the model at predicting that class.

Prepping the Data¶

Before I trained the model I set up a data pipeline which tune the image size and batch size hyperparameters as well as some data augmentation. I experimented with some other augmentation techniques, like adjusting the hue of the images, however, this damaged the performance since the image relies heavily on colour to classify the Pokemon. Note, I have not not rescaled the data at the moment.

In [37]:
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models

IMG_SIZE = 224
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.AUTOTUNE
batch_size = 64

resize = tf.keras.Sequential([
    layers.Resizing(IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
#     layers.Rescaling(1./255)
])

data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
    layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    layers.RandomRotation(0.25),
    layers.RandomZoom(height_factor=(-0.2, 0), width_factor=(-0.2, 0)),
    
])

def prepare(ds, shuffle=False, augment=False):
  # Resize datasets.
    ds = ds.map(lambda x, y: (resize(x), y), 
              num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)
    
    
    if shuffle:
        ds = ds.shuffle(1000)


  # Use data augmentation only on the training set.
    if augment:
        ds = ds.map(lambda x, y: (data_augmentation(x, training=True), y), 
                num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)

    ds = ds.rebatch(batch_size)
  # Use buffered prefetching on all datasets.
    return ds.prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

train_ds = prepare(train_ds, shuffle=True, augment=True)
val_ds = prepare(val_ds)

Defining the Model¶

I attempted a number of different model architectures, including a simple CNN with Conv2D -> BatchNorm -> MaxPool x4 -> Dense x2 -> softmax and the VGG16. Both were taking a long time to train as I am on an old Mac and Tensorflow does not support its GPU and I didn't have access to any cloud GPU systems at the time. As a result, I decided to try MobileNet due to its efficient computations and low training time. I defined the model below:

In [7]:
MobNet = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV3Small(input_shape=(IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3), include_top=False)
MobNet.summary()

Now for fitting the model. I used the Adam optimizer and after trying some learning rates I decided that to start on 0.001 and to reduce on plateau was the most efficient.

The image size was the most impactful hyperparameter on the final accuracy of the model, but also had a significant negative impact training time. I settled on 224 as it was the image size that MobileNet was trained on and produced good results. The batch size that worked best on my CPU was 64, but the impact was small.

In [12]:
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam, SGD

opt = Adam(learning_rate=0.001)
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max', patience=5,  restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor="val_loss", factor=0.1, patience=3, min_lr=0.00001)

model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

model.fit(train_ds, epochs=100,  callbacks=[early_stop, reduce_lr], verbose=False, validation_data=val_ds,   
          steps_per_epoch=train_samples//batch_size+1, validation_steps=val_samples//batch_size+1)

By my count about 10 of these are due to the wrong or more than one Pokemon being shown. Another 10 are misclassifying within the same evolutions e.g. predicting Machoke for a Machamp or Dewgong for a Seel, a forgivable mistake. Finally, many of the other misclassified predictions arise from atypical colours in the image, such as the shiny Tauros and Machamp Pokemon cards or the pink Drowzee predicted as Clefable.

Overall, most of these inaccurate predictions would be removed by fewer mistakes in the validation data or less ambiguous images. Whether you want to go down this route depends on what you intend the model to do, should it be fairly accurate at predicting low res images with a lot of noise or should it be very good at predicting good images that look like a typical depiction of that Pokemon. For now I think 97.7% is very satisfactory and the highest I have seen on the internet.

The logical next step for this project would be to create an operational app for the model to make predictions, and I believe given good inputs it would perform very well. This is something I intend to tackle in the future.

Project Learnings¶

First, the greatest difficulty of the project was the slow training time. I spent a long time trying to get my GPU to work before realising it was not supported. I also had great difficulty getting cloud GPU services to work since the file upload to Google Colab/Drive was erroring often and very slow - something for me to figure out in the future. While MobileNet worked well it was still slower than I'd have liked. Next time I will experiment with freezing a certain number of MobileNet layers and see if I can obtain similar performance.

Second, I learnt not only the importance of data augmentation and that more is not always better. For example, it would be rare to get an image of a Pokemon vertically flipped, as a result augmenting the data in the way was not useful, similarly adjusting the hue of the image made it much hard for the network to learn.

Finally, the quality of data matter hugely to a project like this. I believe I was able to achieve superior accuracy due to the fact I increased the dataset size, however, I am still being let down by incorrectly labeled images or poorly cropped images.

I hope you enjoyed reading and can take inspiration for your own projects in the future!
